The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Hindalco buys Pennar rolling mill

 A STAFF REPORTER

 Calcutta, Jan. 16: Hindalco Industries Ltd has acquired an aluminium rolling mill facility of ailing Pennar Aluminium Company Ltd (PACL).

 The AV Birla group company today informed the stock exchanges that the Asset Reconstruction Company (India) Ltd (Arcil) had accepted its offer to buy certain assets pertaining to aluminium rolling and a conductor rod complex on January 13.

 PACLs facilities are located at its plant at Nagpur, Maharashtra.

 They were put up for sale by Arcil under the Securitisation and Reconstruction of Financial Assets and Enforcement of Security Interest Act, 2002. According to an estimate by the company, the installed capacity in aluminium-rolled products is 30,000 tonnes per annum (tpa) and 14,400 tpa for the conductors. 

 The facility for rolled products was installed in December 1993 and the conductors were installed in November 1994.

 The residual life of the facility for aluminium-rolled products is estimated to be more than 10 years, the company said in a statement. Hindalco acquired these facilities on an as is where is and as is what is basis. 

 The acquisition will also strengthen the leadership position of Hindalco in aluminium-rolled products. It has a 63 per cent market share in the rolled products and 42 per cent in primary aluminium.

 The acquisition news buoyed the scrip on the bourses. On the NSE, the Hindalco stock closed 0.54 per cent or 80 paise up at Rs 149.15, bucking the downward trend witnessed in the market.

 Nalco price rise

 The National Aluminium Company (Nalco) has increased the price of the metal by Rs 2,500 per metric tonne.

 The hike applies to all aluminium products offered by Nalco. 

 We did effect an increase in the price of aluminium from today for all products in view of a corresponding rate hike in the international market, especially in the London Metal Exchange, Nalco chairman and managing director C. R. Pradhan said. 

 Earlier, the PSU had increased aluminium price twice in December 2005 and again on January 1. 




